linear models

# density
tree <- read.csv(here("tree.csv"))
sapling <- read.csv(here("sapling.csv"))
both <- rbind(tree, sapling) ; rm(tree, sapling)
both <- both[both$TREAT !=0,] # removing unburned sites

# basal area
ba <- read.csv(here("ba.csv"), stringsAsFactors = F)
ba <- ba[ba$TREAT != 0,]

Modeling tree density

Conifer tree density

Fire has a significant negative effect, site has a non-significant positive effect.

# conifer tree density
mC_D <- lm(CONIF_COUNT_HA ~ TREAT+ SITE, data = both) 
summary(mC_D); model_parameters(mC_D)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = CONIF_COUNT_HA ~ TREAT + SITE, data = both)
## 
## Residuals:
##    Min     1Q Median     3Q    Max 
## -29.39 -27.86 -12.21   1.89 472.14 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value     Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)   43.498      7.526   5.780 0.0000000132 ***
## TREAT        -15.642      3.312  -4.723 0.0000030306 ***
## SITESTEESE     1.536      5.463   0.281        0.779    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 60.55 on 497 degrees of freedom

## Parameter     | Coefficient |   SE |          95% CI |     t |  df |      p

## (Intercept)   |       43.50 | 7.53 | [ 28.71, 58.29] |  5.78 | 497 | < .001
## TREAT         |      -15.64 | 3.31 | [-22.15, -9.13] | -4.72 | 497 | < .001
## SITE [STEESE] |        1.54 | 5.46 | [ -9.20, 12.27] |  0.28 | 497 | 0.779
# visualizing results
# effect sizes
plot_model(mC_D, show.values = T, show.p = T, sort.est = T)

# predicted values
plot_model(mC_D, type = "pred", terms = c("TREAT", "SITE"))

Im definitely not planning on using any of the predicted values graphs - since 1.5 fires isnt a meaningful value - but theyve been useful in thinking about the differences between sites.

Deciduous tree density

Both fire and site have signifcantly positive effects.

# deciduous density
mD_D <- lm(DECID_COUNT_HA ~ TREAT + SITE, data = both)
summary(mD_D); model_parameters(mD_D)

Modeling basal area

Conifer basal area

Neither fire nor site have significant effects? I think this is because the numbers are so low - theres not really a decline with fire, since that decline happens almost entirely after one fire.

# MODEL -  conifer basal area
  mC_BA <- lm(CONIF_BA ~ TREAT + SITE, data = ba)
  summary(mC_BA); model_parameters(mC_BA)
